        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer791164923" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18144370350850523569">This is arguably the most suspenseful of Remarque&apos;s novels. It is the last work published before Remarque&apos;s death, the third that focuses on the lives of exiles from the Third Reich (after <i>Liebe Deinen Nächsten</i> [<i>Flotsam</i>] and <i>Arc de Triomphe</i>).<br/><br/>The entire novel is set on one night in Lisbon, where the most &quot;fortunate&quot; of exiles who could get that far were able to obtain passage on ships departing for the United States. A man with two tickets on a boat that will soon depart meets another who despera</span>
  <span id="freeText18144370350850523569" style="display:none">This is arguably the most suspenseful of Remarque's novels. It is the last work published before Remarque's death, the third that focuses on the lives of exiles from the Third Reich (after <i>Liebe Deinen Nächsten</i> [<i>Flotsam</i>] and <i>Arc de Triomphe</i>).<br /><br />The entire novel is set on one night in Lisbon, where the most "fortunate" of exiles who could get that far were able to obtain passage on ships departing for the United States. A man with two tickets on a boat that will soon depart meets another who desperately wants to, but cannot, get on the ship. The former promises to give the other his tickets if he will stay the night and listen to his story—a bittersweet, unpredictable story of love, survival and loss.<br /><br />As with all of Remarque's novels, this is a story that shines a light on the reality of life under Nazi rule in ways that no historian could.</span>
