<div id="review_3982006106" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3982006106" />
    <a title="Jim Puskas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7429967-jim-puskas"><img alt="Jim Puskas" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1327280374p2/7429967.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3982006106?book_show_action=true">May 11, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jim Puskas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jim Puskas" href="/user/show/7429967-jim-puskas">Jim Puskas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7429967-jim-puskas?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7429967-jim-puskas?shelf=thriller">thriller</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3982006106" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5289855509151882807">I plan to go back and re-read as many of Remarque’s novels as I can find time for and I decided to start with this, his last. I do so primarily because it’s in this novel that he most powerfully reveals the horrifying nature of the Nazi mindset. The same kind of people, driven by the same sort of evil remain present in our world today. Freedom-loving people everywhere must never forget that menace. To place it all in the harsh light of truth, it&apos;s worth noting that long before this book was publ</span>
  <span id="freeText5289855509151882807" style="display:none">I plan to go back and re-read as many of Remarque’s novels as I can find time for and I decided to start with this, his last. I do so primarily because it’s in this novel that he most powerfully reveals the horrifying nature of the Nazi mindset. The same kind of people, driven by the same sort of evil remain present in our world today. Freedom-loving people everywhere must never forget that menace. To place it all in the harsh light of truth, it's worth noting that long before this book was published, the Nazis despised Remarque so much that they not only banned his books, they beheaded his sister since they could not get their hands on him personally.<br />Most striking is the realization that the refugee’s tragic reality has never changed to this day:<i> When we came, the world’s supply of pity had long been used up. We were nuisances, termites, hardly anyone had a good word for us. We have no right to work, no right to exist and we still have no papers.</i><br />Despite the handicap Remarque imposed upon himself (that of telling the story as a monologue related to another person) it is gripping and drenched with an immediacy of time and place, almost cinematic in its power. Even the fact that we are told at the outset that Helen has died and Schwartz is a man who has lost all hope, does not reduce the emotional impact of his story.<br />There are so many strikingly incisive passages that I could quote; but that would make for an overly long review and could not do the book justice. Instead, I urge everyone to read this novel, set in 1939-40, first published in 1961, and as timely as if it had been written yesterday.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5289855509151882807" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


